                                                       /*FUNCTION CALLING*/
          Functions in C/C++ can be invoked in a way, i.e., to call them into the main function. Whatever function you might have created, you always have to call it in the main body 
          so that the function can be executed. 

          There are 2 methods in which function calling occurs:

          1) {Call By Value}:-

          In call by value method, the value of actual parameters are copied to the functions formal paramters.
          #) There are 2 copies of same parameters stored in different memory locaions.
          #) One is the original copy and other is function copy.
          #) Any changes made inside the functions are not reflected in the actual parameters of the caller.

                                                    // An Exemplary Code

          // A C++ program to swap numbers usimg call by value

        #include<iostream.h>
        #include<conio.h>
        void swap(int x. int y)
        {
        int t;
        t=x;
        x=y;
        y=t;
        cout<<"inside function after swap:\n";
        cout<<" x= "<<x<<" y "<<y<<endl;
        }

        void main()
        {
        int a=10,b=20;
        // using the function
        swap(a,b);
        cout<<"After swap in main\n";
        cout<<" x= "<<a<<" y= "<<b<<endl;
        getch();
        }
      
      Output ;
     ----------------------------------------
     inside function after swap
     x=20,y=10

     after swap in main
     x=10,y=20
     ---------------------------------------- 


     
